snippet.textDisplay:
my new years' resolution is to aim for 50 new years' resolutions of some form. I won't evaluate failure or success in any of them until 1st Jan 2021. Hoping for success in 35/50 but we'll see. I have 13 decided resolutions on the list so far.


The meta-aim of this is to recover from fear of failure. A degree of failure is built into this plan. For some reason, this is making me excited to get stuck in, not terrified of trying and failing anyway. 10/50 is still a good score, and feels achievable while being a lot more successful resolutions than most people get through. One of the resolutions is the dreaded 'get fit/do more exercise'. If this was my only new years' resolution it would be a bleak grind. As it stands I'm excited to get started, but taking it gradually since I have other resolutions to work on too. People who I care about are noticing general improvement, my wellbeing is up and depression down.

The effect I like the most is that it feels like things are getting better, but I don't feel like I'm getting more time-poor or 'imbalanced' like you do when you focus all your energy and time on one change. that's my strat I recommend it!

snippet.textDisplay:
Themes are actually timeless. By getting the illusion of time and the pressure of supposed deadlines out of the way, you're actually living in the moment. Like you wanna practice music yeah just stop watching YT right now grab your instrument. We're so obsessed with goals that we forgot to enjoy life's moments in this eternal now, thinking that there's gonna be a point later on when we'll get to X and we'll be happy.


Whether you will eventually succeed doesn't matter really, because you have to enjoy right now, today. Live as the person who reads books and have fun with it, no matter if you don't manage to complete 1 every month. Fuck goals and deadlines, live the dream.


Also lifestyle identities help us evolve better. I mean you can't be the "person who listen to 1 music album every day" but you can be "the person obsessed with checking out new music".

snippet.textDisplay:
That's an interesting idea but it directly contradicts the typical advice about goal setting. Mainly, it should be specific and measurable. A goal as simple as "I want to lose weight" isn't sufficient. Studies show tome after time that this alone isn't enough. You should say "I want to lose x pounds by y date."

How different is setting the theme of the year to be Losing weight from claiming that you want to lose weight as your new years resolution?

snippet.textDisplay:
This is a strange one to me - pretty much every goal-setting lecture I've ever heard is mostly the opposite. According to those, you want Specific goals that are Measurable - "I will read a new book every month for the rest of the year" is something you can set, check and see if you're on-course, and have a timeline for. Whereas "year of reading" is vague enough that you could construe almost any reading done as success.

It's neat to see a counterpoint here.
